1. Eminem

Eminem is a highly controversial rapper for a multitude of reasons. He successfully challenged the stereotype of black artists dominating the hip-hop industry. His latest album has also picked up traction for having misogynistic and homophobic lyrics. Although I don't regularly listen to Eminem, it's understandable why he's so popular among music enthusiasts. He raps fast for sure, and his lyrics are relatable to many. Some people may just be tired of conforming to society's expectations, and Eminem shows that it's perfectly okay to be contrarian.

2. Ford Model T

This car undoubtedly transformed society. As one of the first mass-produced vehicles, it democratized transportation by allowing anyone to get a ride easily. The car really emphasized the value of innovationsomething that was especially relevant to America, especially since the country was still young compared to the rest of the world. Through its immense success, Ford has established itself as a household name.

assignment_name: In-class Writing: What Beliefs Do We Hold?
raw:
{"id": 10500000403919894, "user_id": 10500000007261170, "url": null, "score": 0.0, "grade": "complete", "excused": false, "attempt": 1, "submission_type": "online_text_entry", "submitted_at": "2025-01-17T23:01:56Z", "body": "

Jorge

What's a story you tell people when they are just starting to get to know you -- and why?

Theres a history of trying out new things, like martial arts, guitar, and piano, but none of them stuck. Martial arts, for example, was dropped right before earning a black belt.

What is something you miss -- and why?

He definitely misses his family after being away for a while, but visiting during breaks helps make up for it.

What is something you regularly look forward to -- and why?

He likes to sleepits a chance to rest and forget about school for a bit. The gym is another go-to, just to blow off steam.

What is a cause you care about -- and why?

Animal rights are important. He has a dog and wants to make it part of the family.

If you could give advice about anything, what are the words of wisdom you'd share -- and why?

"Dont take things too seriously." High school was more about enjoying the experience than stressing out. For instance, barely studying for AP Calculus still led to scoring a 4. Its more about not being too hard on yourself.

What was your favorite trip or vacation -- and why?

Can't think of favorites, but a recent memory was trip to Maine with a girlfriend. They played tennis, a sport she taught him long ago. They had also started dating over the summer.

What is a hobby you can lose yourself in -- and why?

Tennis. It started because of a girlfriend and became something to stick with, especially during high school.

raw:

I was watching an MIT OpenCourseWare lecture on Finance Theory and the instructor Andrew Lo shared a childhood story that traumatized him. Back in the day, he was obsessed with Superman, and always nagged his mother to buy him a Superman suit. Eventually, his mom did buy him the suit, and he spent all morning before school flexing in front of the mirror. Unfortunately, he was late to school. As he walked in the already-filled classroom, he could feel the shame as everyone's eyes were on him. That experience taught Andrew that he would never take longer than five minutes to get dressed.

\n

This stood out to me because a professor shared a humorous yet impactful scene from childhood, to which the audience could relate. Many of us were also probably obsessed too with something.

My topic is about legalizing prostitution in America.

\n

1. A mandate might be forcing sex workers to document their experiences so they are not being abused. It would both benefit and harm the sex workers.
2. An inducement might be giving stipends to businesses to hire people previously involved in the sex industry. It would benefit the former sex workers, but it would harm the companies.
3. A capacity-builder might be spreading more awareness about prostitution through magazines, advertisements, podcasts, etc. It would benefit the former sex workers, but it might harm the general public because it makes them think about taboo topics, as well as organizations funding the campaigns.
4. A system change might be the government changing the way companies hire employees, maybe allowing candidates to omit certain work experience. It would benefit the former sex workers, but it would harm the companies.

1. Which part of this brief was most persuasiveand why?

The part that was most persuasive was the section titled "The growth of nonmedical vaccine exemptions." It highlights a growing problem where some people don't think of diseases as much of a concern now that more people are immune to it. It was interesting that for kindergarteners from '09-'10, the number of philosophical exemptions exceeded the number of religious ones.

2. If you were a policymaker reading this, what would you want added or changed?

If I were a policymaker, I might follow their advice of completely eliminating the personal-belief exemptions since there's no constitutional requirement permitting so. I might also increase the education surrounding vaccines so people are more informed about the dangers of diseases. 

3. Does this brief change your thinking about the issue at all? Why or why not?

Yes. I did not know that many people opted out due to personal reasons. I had always gotten my vaccines because my parents had forced me to.

4. What part of the brief was easiest to understand? What part was confusing or unclear? What would help make it clearer?

Some charts might have helped visualize the numbers, perhaps comparing the different groups of people who opt to not get vaccinated.

{"id": 10500000407504414, "user_id": 10500000007261170, "url": null, "score": 0.0, "grade": "complete", "excused": false, "attempt": 1, "submission_type": "online_text_entry", "submitted_at": "2025-03-31T17:38:01Z", "body": "

1. Many methods could be used to make me care about an issue. When I walk around campus, I see information booths with all sorts of topics. They might make me take a survey in exchange for donuts. A more local example was at my school district, where a gay writer was turned down from presenting his book at the middle school because the school board deemed his lifestyle inappropriate. I definitely cared about the issue, but not enough to take action because I was at the high school at the time.
2. For me to take action demands more serious issues that affect me on the personal level. For one, I attended a presidential rally with my father one of the times because I cared about the future of the country. A more minor issue goes back to the 6th grade, when I realized no one played chess around my neighborhood. So, I started a chess academy and got all the kids together to learn and grow.

Passion blog

1. Exploring the unexpected and often counterintuitive outcomes that arise from seemingly simple or random events. Continuing from last semester, I would write posts on topics that cover probability, chaos, and the impact of small actions on larger systems. Expect to read more about mind games, psychological phenomena, and other interesting topics that challenge your thinking.

2. Table tennis. I played recreationally for over a decade, but I recently started to get serious. In this blog, I will analyze important matches between big players, their playing styles and techniques, and concepts I learned.

Civic issues blog

1. Immigration. I did a group project last semester covering this topic, and I think with the current state of the country, it would definitely be worthwhile to continue down this path. Previously, we investigated how some people see immigration as the backbone of America's legacy, so they are more lax on policies, while others believe letting in too many people through the border compromises the integrity of the country.

2. Education. I moved a couple of times in my grade school days across states and countries. Consequently, I experienced various methods of instruction and could comment on how they've affected me. Looking at the bigger picture, I could get into topics such as a standardized curriculum and the funding gap.

We don't talk about the wars going on. We avoid talking about the Chinese communist party.

When KSI's song released, I thought it sounded pretty good, but most of my friends hated the song.

3. What kind of discussions reveal to you that you and another person fundamentally agree in a broad sense, but really struggle to see eye-to-eye on a more detailed or policy-level scale?

My dad and I both are against abortion and are for gun rights, but I'm not too invested in the specifics to determine which particular stance suits me.

assignment_name: In-class Writing: What Problems Do We Care About?
raw:
{"id": 10500000401216489, "user_id": 10500000007261170, "url": null, "score": 0.0, "grade": "complete", "excused": false, "attempt": 1, "submission_type": "online_text_entry", "submitted_at": "2025-03-07T18:50:25Z", "body": "

One of the most pressing issues that is relevant to me is the job market for computer science graduates. As a computer science student, there's a lot of pressure to land somewhere good amidst the growing competition of other students in the same shoes. Companies are becoming more selective and interviews are painstakingly hard.

\n

Another issue is the high cost of living. It's hard to imagine buying a house for hundreds of thousands of dollars right out of college. Nothing is given for free, and luck is often involved to get where you want to be.

\n

A third issue is more pertinent to my high school. The way the system is structured encourages students to engage in academic dishonesty to achieve high grades.

{"id": 10500000401216650, "user_id": 10500000007261170, "url": null, "score": 0.0, "grade": "complete", "excused": false, "attempt": 1, "submission_type": "online_text_entry", "submitted_at": "2025-04-08T02:01:20Z", "body": "

How do you feel about your delivery method of choice? What do you think makes it compelling and an appropriate fit for your topic?

I feel like my delivery method is perfect for my topic. It allows the audience to feel the consequences of policies surrounding prostitution in real time by putting them in the shoes of an affected individual.

What are you planning to inspire or convince your audience to do? How are you considering doing it?

I want to inspire my audience to question the effectiveness of criminalization and consider why legalization may be a better approach. The RPG will do this by simulating the lived experience of someone trying to survive under different legal frameworks (e.g., criminalized, Nordic model, legalized). The player will encounter key eventslike police encounters, medical needs, client screening, or economic strugglesthat play out differently depending on the policy in place.

Who is your target audience and what are some considerations you are making related to your target audience? How does this audience differ from that of your Issue Brief?

My target audience is probably high school and college-age people who may not yet have a strong opinion on the issue but are open to learning. I've played many video games before, so I know our generation is more digitally inclined, so they are more likely to engage with a game than a traditional policy paper.

This audience differs from the Issue Brief's audience, which is composed of policymakers and educators. While the Issue Brief uses an academic tone and data to persuade, the RPG appeals to emotion and experience.

1. What do you hope this website accomplishes?

I'm double-majoring in computer science and economics, and my goals are very focused. As a result, I want this website to show a different side of myself that's not so academic. I want people to discover this website to get to know me better. I don't intend for it to be used in a professional context, but rather as an icebreaker to meet new people.

2. Who would you like to reach?

General audience. Maybe link it on my socials so people can preview me before connecting.

3. What content have you included (or will include) to better accomplish the above? Remember that this project requires 5-10 items total and a minimum of 3 items from 137H/138T.

A timeline (could be a photo album)
- This I Believe - an event from childhood
- civic artifact - games I like
- paradigm shift - my music taste

My intellectual drive
- passion blog
- could also have work from outside school here

Activism
- advocacy project
- civics issue blog

4. What arrangement or design choices have you made (or plan to make) to help achieve that?

I'm coding the website myself to have full customization on the content. I can add a contact form that emails me when someone submits. Maybe throw in some testimonials. Visually appealing effects could be incorporated if time permits.

5. What criteria of this assignment do you think will be most challenging for you?

Organization. How do I communicate myself most effectively to a stranger coming across my portfolio? I need to strike the perfect balance of content and effectiveness. Each tab should be themed for a particular topic. The order in which the artifacts are presented would also play a big role.
